{0 Document synchronization}

How the server keeps its in-memory view of the vault consistent with
disk as the user opens, edits, saves, and closes files.

{1 State}

Held by {!Lsp_lib.Server}:

{ul
  {- [vault]: a {!Oystermark.Vault.t} holding the index, pre-resolved
     docs, and vault root.  Built from disk; rebuilt on didOpen and
     didSave.}
  {- [open_docs]: vault-relative path → buffer content, for every
     document the editor currently has open.  It answers two
     questions: {i which} files need a diagnostic refresh after a
     save, and what the user is currently looking at in a file whose
     edits are unsaved.}
}

{1 Current behavior}

{b This section describes what the server does today.  The
buffer-vs-disk story is not yet settled — see
{{!section-"open-questions"}Open questions} below.}

Handlers split into two groups by which content they answer against:

{ul
  {- {b Buffer}: diagnostics, hover, go-to-definition, completion.
     These are anchored at the cursor, so they read the open buffer
     and reflect unsaved edits immediately.  Resolution still happens
     against the last-built vault, so a link to a note created but
     not yet saved stays unresolved.}
  {- {b Disk}: find references, rename, document outline, inlay
     hints, code actions.  These range over the whole vault, where
     mixing one live buffer with N stale files would be more
     confusing than being uniformly one save behind.}
}

{1 Notification handling}

{2 [textDocument/didOpen]}

{ol
  {- Record the document's rel_path and content in [open_docs].}
  {- Rebuild the vault from disk.  This catches files that were added
     out-of-band since the last rebuild.}
  {- Publish diagnostics for the opened document, computed against
     [content] from the notification.}
}

{2 [textDocument/didChange]}

Update the document's entry in [open_docs], then recompute and
publish diagnostics against the new content.  [vault] is {i not}
rebuilt, so link resolution — and every disk-reading handler —
continues to see the pre-edit state.

{2 [textDocument/didSave]}

{ol
  {- Rebuild the vault from disk.  The saved file's new content is
     now part of the vault, along with any other files that changed
     on disk as a side-effect of the save.}
  {- For every entry in [open_docs], read its current disk content
     and republish diagnostics.  This is what clears stale warnings
     in sibling buffers when the save caused them to become
     resolvable.}
}

{2 [textDocument/didClose]}

Remove the entry from [open_docs].  No rebuild.

{1 Observable consequences}

{ul
  {- Unsaved edits don't affect the vault-wide features.  Adding a
     new [[[note-x]]] link to an unsaved buffer and immediately
     running find-references on [note-x] will not show the new
     link.}
  {- Diagnostics for the active buffer are live — the squiggly under
     an unresolved link appears and disappears as the user types.}
  {- Diagnostics for sibling buffers refresh only on save.  If [a.md]
     is open with an unresolved [[[b]]] link, creating [b.md] in
     another tab only clears [a.md]'s warning once a save fires.}
  {- Out-of-band file changes (e.g. [git checkout]) are only picked
     up on the next didOpen or didSave.}
}

{1:mixed-frame Hazard: mixed position frames}

{b The split above is not clean, and the seam is worth naming
explicitly.}

An LSP request carries a position — a [(line, character)] pair — that
the client computed against {e its own buffer}. The disk-group
handlers then convert that position to a byte offset against {e disk}
content. When the buffer has unsaved edits above the cursor, the two
disagree, and the handler resolves a different location than the one
the user's cursor is on.

This is a different failure from the staleness described above.
Answering one save behind is a defensible tradeoff: the answer is
{e old but coherent}. Indexing a live coordinate into stale content is
neither — the byte offset is meaningless, so the answer is about
whatever text happens to sit there now.

The consequences differ by handler:

{ul
  {- {b find references}, {b prepare rename}, {b document outline},
     {b inlay hints}: a wrong-or-empty result. Annoying, recoverable,
     visibly wrong to the user.}
  {- {b rename} and {b code actions}: these {e return edits}, with
     byte ranges derived from disk content, which the client then
     applies to the {e buffer}. A shifted range does not fail loudly;
     it silently rewrites the wrong span of a file the user is
     editing.}
}

Until the split is resolved, treat rename and code actions on a dirty
buffer as unsound rather than merely stale. The narrow fix is to
resolve the request's own position — and compute any returned edit
ranges — against [open_docs] content whenever the file is open, even
while vault-wide {e scanning} continues to read from disk. The broad
fix is the first open question below.

{1:open-questions Open questions}

{ul
  {- {b Should the vault-wide handlers honor unsaved buffer content
     too?}  The buffers are already held in [open_docs]; what is
     missing is re-resolving links against them on didChange rather
     than rebuilding the vault from disk.  The current split is
     simpler but can surprise users who expect find-references to
     reflect what they see on screen — and, per
     {{!section-"mixed-frame"}the hazard above}, it is what makes
     rename and code actions unsound on a dirty buffer.  Not yet
     decided.}
  {- {b Should diagnostics recompute on didChange at all?}  Keeping
     them live is ergonomic but inconsistent with the rest of the
     feature set answering from disk.  The alternative is to refresh
     everything only on save.}
}
